<P>
 * As the daughter of a man who died in Vietnam in 1971, and as a member of the 
national organization, Sons and Daughters in Touch, I was surprised to hear of 
the return of 12 sets of remains four days after the U.S.-Vietnam trade embargo 
was lifted (Feb. 8). I applaud the healing motion of lifting the embargo. I 
feel that because the media made so little of the return of the remains, 
another opportunity for the healing of this nation's sorrow over Vietnam was 
lost. Let's please give any subsequent homecomings the respect and media 
attention those heroes deserve. After all, even Achilles showed respect for 
Hector by eating a ceremonial burial feast with Priam, Hector's mourning 
father. 
</P>
<P>
 STACY TUMLIN 
