<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERMIT REJECTED FOR NUDE-DANCING BAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LILY DIZON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council on Monday rejected a permit for what would have been the 
city's first nude-dancing bar. 
</P>
<P>
 After passionate pleas from residents urging them to reject the bar's 
application, the council members voted unanimously to deny a permit to the 
Mermaid, at 4248 Martingale Way, in Newport Place Planned Community. 
</P>
<P>
 Ronald Talmo, attorney for the owners of the Mermaid, said he will probably 
file a federal civil lawsuit against the city, alleging that the action of the 
council members violated his client's First Amendment rights. 
</P>
<P>
 Talmo had claimed that the Mermaid, which would offer live nude and topless 
dancing, would be a theater and therefore protected. 
</P>
<P>
 Ironically, the City Council used the same theater argument to keep the 
Mermaid from opening. 
</P>
<P>
 According to City Atty. Robert Burnham, the zoning standards for the Newport 
Place Planned Community do not allow for a theater.LILY DIZON 
</P>
</TEXT>
