</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEY BRIEFING: TALLYING THE DAMAGE; ANALYSIS SHOWS ERRATIC PATTERN OF 
DESTRUCTION ACROSS VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Northridge earthquake's destruction in the San Fernando Valley was 
erratic, sparing buildings in some communities near the epicenter and toppling 
structures miles away. It caused about $1 billion in structural damage in the 
Valley, about half the estimated total citywide. Outside of Cal State 
Northridge, the Valley ZIP code with the highest repair estimates is in Sherman 
Oaks, according to a Times computer analysis of Los Angeles Dept. of Building 
and Safety lists of structures determined unsafe or safe for limited use. Why a 
ZIP code several miles from the epicenter would be hit harder than closer areas 
is a question facing scientists who will be studying the quake for months or 
even years to come.  
</P>
<P>
 Shown is a rundown by ZIP code of earthquake damage cost estimates and number 
of structures determined to be unsafe or safe only for limited entry. 
Non-residential refers to businesses, as well as hospitals, schools and 
religious buildings. Valley Totals 
</P>
